{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655205"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.06,0.06,0,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114862"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11389"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96868"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7250"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26695"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114862"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn\u0027s skull contains several fontanelles where bones have not yet fused. These areas are important for both birth and early development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anterior fontanelle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Triangular in shape and located between parietal bones","Oval in shape and located between temporal bones","Circular in shape and located between occipital bones","Rectangular in shape and located between sphenoid bones","Diamond in shape and located between frontal and parietal bones"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior fontanelle (image) is \u003Cstrong\u003Ediamond in shape and located between frontal and parietal bones\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the largest fontanelle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriangular in shape and located between parietal bones\u003C/strong\u003E better describes the posterior fontanelle, which is smaller and triangular. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal bones do not form a major fontanelle\u003C/strong\u003E, making the oval shape and temporal bone location incorrect. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital bone is single and does not form a fontanelle with itself\u003C/strong\u003E, so circular shape between occipital bones is anatomically inaccurate. Similarly, the \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid is a single bone and does not form a fontanelle with itself\u003C/strong\u003E, making the rectangular description incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior fontanelle serves several important functions: it allows the skull to deform slightly during birth and accommodates rapid brain growth in infancy. It closes between 18-24 months of age.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior fontanelle is diamond-shaped and located at the intersection of the frontal and parietal bones.","Fontanelles allow for brain growth and slight compression during birth.","The anterior fontanelle closes between 18-24 months of age."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Skull of a new-born child from above\u0022 by Dr. Johannes Sobotta is under Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Sobo_1909_105.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"i